2004-10-05

  New features:
   - generate a WSDL file from the Lisp definition of a service
   - examine the namespace configuration in a WSDL file and
       choose a namespace-to-package mapping

  Enhancements and corrections:
   - extensive revisions of WSDL parsing and generation
   - we can now parse and generate interfaces for 357 of 370 
       definitions on xmethods.com (both rpc and document styles)
   - summary information in generated client or server file
   - soap-message-client can now specify a proxy

  Changed behavior:
   - revised the namespace-to-package mapping concept with
		new syntax and new operators
   - make-server-interface, make-client-interface:
		The eval argument is ignored.
   - eliminated all the namespace variables

Details:

soap-message-client    NEW keyword arguments: start  trim-whitespace  soap-debug
                                              base-dns

soap-message-server    NEW keyword arguments: name service-name url port-name
                                              binding-name  base-dns
                                              trim-whitespace  soap-debug

NEW accessors for soap-connector
   soap-port-name
   soap-binding-name
   soap-service-name

enable-soap-server server &key &allow-other-keys

disable-soap-server server &key &allow-other-keys

start-soap-server server &key new start enable &allow-other-keys

stop-soap-server  server &key disable &allow-other-keys

wsdl-server-names wsdl-file-connector

make-client-interface    make-server-interface
   NEW keyword arguments: port if-missing-package

encode-wsdl-file file &key namespaces servers target name (if-exists :supersede)

decode-wsdl-namespaces &key file string uri base

NEW operator define-namespace to make a global namespace definition

NEW operator define-namespace-map to make a named, global
		namespace-to-package mapping

NEW variables *soap-client-debug* and *soap-server-debug*


